ORACLE SQL Languages :
=========================
1. Data Definition Language (DDL): CREATE, ALTER, DROP, TRUNCATE, RENAME AND COMMENT.
  
    CREATE Operations:
    ===================
         SQL> create table emp(id number,name varchar2(25),dob date,place number);
         SQL> CREATE a table copy from existing table with data (CTAS Method):
         SQL> create table emp as select * from employee;

      ALTER Operations:
    ===================
          SQL> alter table emp rename column dob to data_of_birth;
          SQL> alter table emp modify (place varchar(50));
          SQL> alter table emp drop column place;
          SQL> alter table emp add salary number(8,2);
          SQL> alter table emp rename to employee;

      DROP Operation:
      ===================
         SQL> drop table emp;

      TRUNCATE Operation:
      ===================
         SQL> truncate table emp;

      COMMENT for Column:
      ===================
              In Oracle, you add comments to tables and columns using the COMMENT statement.
               SQL> comment on column employee.name is 'emp name';
          
              Add a comment to a table
              ======================================
                     SQL> COMMENT ON TABLE patients IS 'Stores patient demographic information';
              
              Add a comment to a column
               =================== ===================
                     SQL> COMMENT ON COLUMN patients.patient_id IS 'Primary key of patients table';
                     SQL> COMMENT ON COLUMN patients.birth_date IS 'Date of birth of the patient';
                     SQL> COMMENT ON COLUMN patients.province_id IS 'Province code referencing province_names';
              
              View comments:
              ===================
                  Table comments:
                   SQL> 
                      SELECT table_name, comments
                      FROM user_tab_comments
                      WHERE table_name = 'PATIENTS';
              
              Column comments:
                     SQL> 
                      SELECT table_name, column_name, comments
                      FROM user_col_comments
                      WHERE table_name = 'PATIENTS';
              
              Update / remove a comment:
              ==========================
              Just re-run the command:
                     SQL> COMMENT ON TABLE patients IS NULL;
              
              Best practice:
              ==============
                --> Use comments for business meaning, not obvious SQL
                --> Always comment PKs, FKs, and important columns
                --> Helpful for data dictionary & audits

2. Data Manipulation Language (DML): INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE and MERGE.

    INSERT Operations:
    ===================
          SQL> insert into employee values(1,'mani','16-apr-1992',30000);
          SQL> insert into employee (id,name)values(2,'arun');
          SQL> insert into employee values(&id,'&name','&date_of_birth',&salary);
    UPDATE Operations:
    ===================
     SQL> update employee set data_of_birth='23-sep-1998' where id=2;
     SQL> update employee set name='madhan',salary=50000 where id=1;
     SQL> update set a.age=b.age when not matched then insert (id,age)values(b.id,b.age);
    
    DELETE Operations
    ===================
     SQL> delete from employee where id=3;
     SQL> delete from employee;
    
    MERGE Operation:
    ===================
     SQL> merge into employee a using salary b on (a.id=b.id) when matched then

3. Data Control Language (DCL): GRANT and REVOKE.
     SQL> grant select on employee to siva;
     SQL> grant insert,update on salary to siva;
     SQL> revoke update on salary from siva;

3. Transaction Control Language (TCL): COMMIT, ROLLBACK, and SAVEPOINT.
     SQL> show autocommit;
     commit;
     rollback;
     savepoint a;
     savepoint b;
     savepoint c;
     savepoint d;
     rollback to b;

4. Data Retrieval Language (DRL): SELECT.
     SQL> select * from employee;
     SQL> select id,name from employee;
     SQL> select name from employee where id=2;
